{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"The conversation history passed to the LLM is trimmed to the most recent 10 messages when the full history exceeds the context window.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: the failure boundary is the handoff between history management and LLM request construction (which messages are actually sent), not just isolated list-slicing logic. REAL-INFRA: no real OS/network/subprocess is required; an in-process LLM client stub can capture payload. LLM-DEP: correctness does not depend on model judgment, only payload content. MULTI-STEP: no multi-agentic chain required. REJECTION-GATE: System/Agentic/Workflow were rejected because the behavior text is strictly about what is passed to the LLM, not real HTTP/OS effects or output quality.","test_description":"Wire chatbot service + prompt builder + an in-memory LLM client stub that records request input. Feed a history longer than 10 messages and assert exactly the latest 10 messages (correct order and roles) are included in the LLM call.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.35,"Integration":0.6,"System":0.02,"Agentic":0.02,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"The generated response addresses the customer's question rather than producing a generic or off-topic reply.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"LLM-DEP: this is directly about response relevance/quality, which depends on real model output and can vary across runs. MOCK-HIDE: a stubbed response would always pass and cannot expose off-topic/generic generation failures. MULTI-STEP: single generation quality check, so Agentic not Workflow. REJECTION-GATE: Integration was rejected because behavior text evaluates semantic quality ('addresses the question') rather than infrastructure around the call.","test_description":"Run the real model on a curated set of customer questions with conversation context. Score each output for direct answer relevance (rubric or blinded judge) and fail if relevance drops below threshold or off-topic rate exceeds limit.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.03,"System":0.04,"Agentic":0.82,"Workflow":0.1}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"The tone re-check correctly identifies when a response is too formal for a casual-tier customer and triggers regeneration.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"LLM-DEP: 'correctly identifies' tone appropriateness is a model judgment problem; deterministic mocks hide classification failures. MOCK-MISS/MOCK-HIDE: trigger wiring can be integration-tested, but correctness of the formal-vs-casual decision needs real AI output. MULTI-STEP: behavior requires one agentic decision (tone classification) and a trigger action; does not require validating a full multi-agentic sequence outcome. REJECTION-GATE: Workflow was considered but rejected because this behavior text focuses on detection + trigger, not end-to-end correctness across multiple model decisions.","test_description":"Execute tone-check with real model-based evaluator on responses likely to be overly formal for casual tier; assert formality is flagged and regeneration path is invoked for flagged cases.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.02,"Integration":0.08,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.7,"Workflow":0.15}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"The full exchange (user message, generated response, any regenerations) is persisted to the database with correct timestamps.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: failure appears in module wiring among chat orchestration, regeneration tracking, and persistence layer. REAL-INFRA: a local test DB/in-process persistence is sufficient; no real external network/OS primitive is required. LLM-DEP: assertions are about stored records/timestamps, not model quality. MULTI-STEP: not a multi-agentic correctness requirement. REJECTION-GATE: System/Agentic/Workflow were rejected because behavior text is persistence integrity and timestamping.","test_description":"Run chatbot flow against a local test database, including a forced regeneration case, then assert all expected records exist (user input, first draft, regenerated response), linked to one conversation, with correct and monotonic timestamps.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.05,"Integration":0.83,"System":0.09,"Agentic":0.02,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"When the tone check triggers regeneration, the second response replaces the first — the customer never sees the rejected draft.","minimum_level":"Workflow","justification":"INTEGRATION-BRAKE(d): this is orchestration/state handoff across LLM-involved stages (initial generation -> tone decision -> regeneration -> user delivery). MULTI-STEP: requires multiple sequential model-mediated steps, and correctness depends on end-to-end gating of what is surfaced to the customer. MOCK-HIDE: stubbing all model steps can miss sequencing defects that appear when real outputs/timing drive branch behavior. REJECTION-GATE: Integration and Agentic were considered but not retained because behavior text explicitly spans the full sequence and final user-visible outcome ('never sees the rejected draft').","test_description":"Run the full pipeline with real generation and real tone-check/regeneration enabled. Capture outbound customer-visible message channel and internal logs; assert only regenerated response is delivered while rejected draft is retained only in internal audit/persistence.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.12,"System":0.07,"Agentic":0.25,"Workflow":0.55}}]}
